  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 25-31.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - These verses have for their primary object, not to give an exhaustive summary of the wealth of David and the sources thereof, but to give the names of those persons who were charged with the care, or the management and care, of' it. The classification, however, is interesting, and may be naturally expected to be tolerably complete. We do not find any distinction made between such property as might have belonged to David as private property, and such as belonged to him as king - probably because there was none worth making. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 25.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - For ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "storehouses",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", read, as in former clause, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "treasures.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The suggestion of the second half of this verse in comparison with the first is that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Azmaveth's",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " charge was over treasures in Jerusalem. For the castles, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 17:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 27:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אוצָר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", though the same in both clauses, may probably enough cover precious treasure, as of gold, silver, costly raiment, etc. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 14:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 15:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), more particularly in the first clause, and grain, fruit, etc. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 11:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), in the latter, for the word has distinctly this double application. (See for some illustration of this verse also, Sallust., 'De Belle Jugurth.,' 12.) 1 Chronicles 27:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The managers of David's possessions and domains. - The property and the income of the king were (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") divided into treasures of the king, and treasures in the country, in the cities, the villages, and the castles. By the \"treasures of the king\" we must therefore understand those which were in Jerusalem, i.e., the treasures of the royal palace. These were managed by Azmaveth. The remaining treasures are specified in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". They consisted in fields which were cultivated by labourers (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); in vineyards (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); plantations of olive trees and sycamores in the Shephelah, the fruitful plain on the Mediterranean Sea (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); in cattle, which pastured partly in the plain of Sharon between Caesarea Palestina and Joppa, partly in various valleys of the country (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and in camels, asses, and sheep (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 27:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). All these possessions are called רכוּשׁ, and the overseers of them הרכוּשׁ שׂרי. They consisted in the produce of agriculture and cattle-breeding, the two main branches of Israelitish industry. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]